<tr>
<td colspan="3" class="boilerplate metadata" style="line-height:10pt; padding:0.5em;"><small><b>Note</b>: This page may contain <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">IPA</a> phonetic symbols in <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a>.</small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Glosa</b> is an <a href="/wiki/International_auxiliary_language" title="International auxiliary language">international auxiliary language</a> based on a previous auxiliary called <a href="/wiki/Interglossa" title="Interglossa">Interglossa</a>. As an <a href="/wiki/Isolating_language" title="Isolating language">isolating language</a>, there are no <a href="/wiki/Inflection" title="Inflection">inflections</a>, so that words remain always in their original form, no matter what function they have in the sentence. However, some grammatical functions are taken over by a small number of operator words and by the use of word order (<a href="/wiki/Syntax" title="Syntax">syntax</a>).</p>
<p><br /></p>
